<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12045k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12045k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12045k"> 45(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ anathema on robs / vae!</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Dans un autre ouvrage, le scribe a &eacute;crit de mauvais vers latins, &agrave; la suite d&apos;un hymne de saint Ambroise: &lsquo;Vive la main qui a pris soin d&apos;&eacute;crire si bien! Si quelqu&apos;un veut savoir, le nom du copiste, le voici: &laquo;c&apos;est le fr&egrave;re F&eacute;lix Fr&eacute;mond qu&apos;on doit aimer &agrave; travers les &acirc;g&eacute;s! &rsquo; Un autre ajoute ceci &agrave; un sermon de saint Augustin: &lsquo;Moi, tr&egrave;s humble nourrisson de saint Michel, j&apos;ai nom G&eacute;rard; j&apos;ai transcrit ce doux volume, afin de m&eacute;riter la gr&acirc;ce du Christ qui est dans les cieux. &rsquo; Un autre r&eacute;clame instamment une pri&egrave;re: &lsquo;A quiconque dira pour l&apos;&acirc;me du copiste un pater et un ave, que Dieu lui fasse la gr&acirc;ce d&apos;avoir une place dans un lieu de rafra&icirc;chissement, de lumi&egrave;re et de paix. &rsquo; / Un moine copiant du S&eacute;n&egrave;que, constate <font color="green">[35]</font> avec tristesse (on est aux mauvais jours de la Guerre de Cent Ans), que l&apos;ordre des choses est boulevers&eacute;; la pens&eacute;e est jolie et po&eacute;tiquement exprim&eacute;e: &lsquo;Miles in claustro, monachus in pr&oelig;lio, azur in c&oelig;lo. &rsquo; / Enfin plusieurs manuscrits portent des mentions d&apos;anath&egrave;me contre ceux qui oseraient s&apos;emparer ind&ucirc;ment des ouvrages appartenant &agrave; la biblioth&egrave;que b&eacute;n&eacute;dictine &laquo;Quicumque hunc librum furatur, anathema sit. Fiat, Fiat in Domino.&raquo; Relevons, enfin, une curieuse annotation, faite en marge de l&apos;histoire d&apos;un abb&eacute;, dont la conduite et l&apos;administration avaient &eacute;t&eacute; vivement critiqu&eacute;es par les religieux: <i>Vae, vae, vae</i> a &eacute;crit par trois fois une main tremblante et vengeresse. <br><font color="green">[In another work, the scribe has written bad Latin verses, following a hymn by Saint Ambrose: &lsquo;Long live the hand that has written so well! If someone wants to know the name of the scribe, here it is: It is brother F&eacute;lix Fr&eacute;mond who needs to be loved through the ages!&rsquo; Another adds the following to a sermon by saint Augustin: &lsquo;Me, the very humble child of saint Michel, my name is G&eacute;rard; <mark>I have transcribed this sweet volume, in order to get credit from the grace of Christ who is in heaven</mark>.&rsquo; Still another demands a quick prayer: &lsquo;To anyone who prays for the soul of the scribe a pater and an ave, may God give him with grace <mark>a place in a location where there will be refreshment</mark>, light and peace.&rsquo; A monk copying Seneca, finds with sadness (we are in the worst years of the Hundred Year war), that everything has been turned upside down; the thought is beautiful and poetically worded: &lsquo;Soldiers in the cloister, monks are fighting, blue in the sky.&rsquo; Also several manuscripts carry anathemas against those who unlawfully would acquire the volumes belonging to the Benedictine library. <i>Quicumque hunc librum furatur, anathema sit. <mark>Fiat, Fiat in Domino</mark></i>. Finally let me mention a strange note in the margin of a history of an abbot, whose administration and behaviour had been criticized strongly by the clerics: <i><mark>Vae, vae, vae</mark></i> has been written three times a trembling and vengeful hand.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 35-6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: L. <i>Vae!</i>: Woe!</mm> </dd></dl>
